    <h2>1. Understanding the Types: Mixer Grinder vs Wet Grinder vs Dry Grinder vs Pulverizer</h2>

    <p>Before looking at prices, it's critical to understand that "mixer grinder" is a broad category that covers fundamentally different machines. Each type uses a different grinding mechanism and is optimized for different ingredients. Buying the wrong type means poor results, wasted ingredients, and equipment damage.</p>

    <h3>Jar Mixer Grinder (Commercial Grade)</h3>
    <p>A commercial jar mixer grinder works on the same principle as a domestic mixer grinder — a high-speed blade rotates inside a jar, cutting and blending ingredients. The commercial version has a far more powerful motor (1–3 HP vs 500–750W in domestic), heavier blades, thicker stainless steel jars, and a motor designed for continuous duty. These machines typically come with 2–5 jars of different sizes for wet grinding, dry grinding, and blending.</p>
    <p>Jar mixer grinders are the most versatile option. They handle chutneys, masala pastes, batters (in smaller quantities), spice powders, smoothies, and liquid blending. They are the standard all-purpose grinder for most North Indian restaurants, multi-cuisine kitchens, and small to mid-size food businesses.</p>

    <h3>Wet Grinder (Tilting & Table-Top)</h3>
    <p>A wet grinder uses heavy granite or stone rollers that rotate inside a drum, crushing and grinding soaked ingredients into a smooth paste or batter. The grinding action is completely different from a jar mixer grinder — instead of cutting with blades at high speed, a wet grinder slowly crushes ingredients between stone surfaces. This produces a finer, smoother batter with better texture and fermentation characteristics.</p>
    <p>Wet grinders are essential for South Indian food businesses. Idli batter, dosa batter, and many chutneys require the specific texture that only stone grinding can produce. A jar mixer grinder can make a passable batter in small quantities, but for commercial-quality South Indian food, a dedicated wet grinder is non-negotiable.</p>
    <p>Tilting wet grinders have a mechanism to tilt the drum for easy pouring — essential when you're working with 10–40 litres of batter at a time. Table-top wet grinders are smaller, counter-mounted units suitable for smaller operations.</p>

    <h3>Commercial Dry Grinder</h3>
    <p>A commercial dry grinder is purpose-built for grinding dry ingredients — whole spices, dried chillies, turmeric, coriander, lentils, grains, and other dry materials into fine powders or flours. These machines use hammer mills, plate mills, or high-speed blade mechanisms to pulverize dry ingredients efficiently.</p>
    <p>While a jar mixer grinder can do dry grinding in small batches (using the dry grinding jar), a dedicated commercial dry grinder processes much larger volumes, produces finer and more consistent powders, and does it faster. If your business involves grinding its own spice blends, making besan or rice flour, or processing dry ingredients in quantities above 500g per batch, a dedicated dry grinder is worth the investment.</p>

    <h3>Pulverizer</h3>
    <p>A pulverizer is the heavy-duty industrial version of a dry grinder. It uses a high-speed hammer mechanism to pulverize ingredients into extremely fine powder. Pulverizers are used in spice processing businesses, flour mills, and large-scale food manufacturing — they are typically not needed for a single restaurant, but larger catering businesses and food processing units may require one. Pulverizer prices start around ₹25,000 and go up to ₹2,00,000+ for industrial units.</p>

