    <h2>2. Commercial Jar Mixer Grinder: Prices, Specs & Buying Guide</h2>

    <p>The jar mixer grinder is the workhorse of the Indian commercial kitchen. Almost every restaurant, hotel, and catering business owns at least one. Here's everything you need to know about choosing the right commercial jar mixer grinder in 2026.</p>

    <h3>How Commercial Jar Mixer Grinders Work</h3>
    <p>A commercial jar mixer grinder has a powerful motor base and multiple stainless steel jars that lock onto the base. Inside each jar is a set of sharp stainless steel blades. When the motor runs, the blades rotate at high speed (typically 15,000–22,000 RPM), cutting, blending, and grinding the ingredients inside the jar. Different jars are designed for different tasks — wet grinding jars have different blade configurations than dry grinding jars, and liquidizer jars are optimized for blending liquids.</p>

    <h3>Key Specifications to Understand</h3>
    <p><strong>Motor Power (HP / Watts):</strong> Commercial jar mixer grinders range from 1 HP (750W) to 3 HP (2,250W). For a restaurant serving 50–100 covers per day, a 1.5 HP mixer grinder is sufficient. For larger operations or continuous use, go for 2 HP or above. Never buy a unit rated below 1 HP for commercial use — it will overheat and burn out within months.</p>
    <p><strong>Number of Jars:</strong> Most commercial units come with 2–5 jars. A standard 3-jar set includes a large liquidizer jar (2–3 litres), a medium wet grinding jar (1–1.5 litres), and a small dry grinding jar (0.5–1 litre). Some models offer 4 or 5 jars with specialized configurations for specific tasks like chutney grinding or juicing.</p>
    <p><strong>Jar Material:</strong> Always choose stainless steel jars for commercial use. Polycarbonate (plastic) jars crack under heavy use, stain, and absorb odours. Stainless steel is more durable, hygienic, and suitable for hot ingredients. The grade of stainless steel matters — look for SS 304 food-grade steel. Avoid aluminum jars entirely in a commercial setting.</p>
    <p><strong>RPM (Revolutions Per Minute):</strong> Higher RPM means finer grinding but also more heat generation. For most restaurant applications, 18,000–22,000 RPM is ideal. Some models offer variable speed control, which is useful for different tasks — low speed for coarse grinding, high speed for fine pastes.</p>
    <p><strong>Overload Protection:</strong> Essential in commercial settings. Overload protection automatically cuts power to the motor when it's strained beyond its capacity — for example, when grinding too-hard ingredients or when the jar is overfilled. Without overload protection, a strained motor will burn out. Every serious commercial mixer grinder has this feature, but verify it before buying.</p>

