    <h2>3. Tilting Wet Grinder: Prices, Specs & Buying Guide</h2>

    <p>The tilting wet grinder is the backbone of every serious South Indian restaurant and hotel. If you serve idli, dosa, vada, or any South Indian preparation that requires stone-ground batter, a tilting wet grinder is not optional — it's essential. Here's everything you need to know about commercial wet grinder prices and how to choose the right one.</p>

    <h3>How Tilting Wet Grinders Work</h3>
    <p>A tilting wet grinder consists of a stainless steel drum (the grinding vessel) with two or three cylindrical granite stones (called rollers) that sit inside. The drum rotates, and the rollers turn against the drum bottom and walls, crushing and grinding soaked ingredients between the stone surfaces. The "tilting" part refers to a mechanism — usually a handle or wheel — that allows you to tilt the entire drum to pour out the ground batter without having to scoop it out manually.</p>

    <p>The stone-grinding action is what makes wet grinders irreplaceable for South Indian batters. When rice and urad dal are ground between stones, the grinding action aerates the batter and creates a texture that promotes natural fermentation. Blade-ground batters (from mixer grinders) don't ferment as well because the cutting action heats the batter and produces a different texture. For authentic, fluffy idlis and crispy dosas, stone-ground batter from a wet grinder is the gold standard.</p>

    <h3>Tilting Wet Grinder Capacity: Choosing the Right Size</h3>
