    <p>A critical point about capacity: never fill a wet grinder to its full rated capacity. For best results, fill it to 75–80% of rated capacity. A 10-litre wet grinder should be loaded with 7.5–8 litres of soaked ingredients plus water. Overfilling produces uneven grinding and strains the motor.</p>

    <h3>Key Specifications for Tilting Wet Grinders</h3>
    <p><strong>Grinding Stones:</strong> The quality of the granite stones determines the quality of the grind. Look for natural granite stones — synthetic or composite stones are cheaper but wear out faster and don't produce the same batter quality. Better brands like Lakshmi, Premier, and Santha use hand-selected granite stones that are balanced for even grinding.</p>
    <p><strong>Drum Material:</strong> The drum should be food-grade stainless steel (SS 304). Some cheaper models use SS 202 or even aluminum-lined drums — avoid these. SS 304 is more corrosion-resistant, hygienic, and durable. The drum thickness also matters — thicker drums (1mm+) last longer and resist denting.</p>
    <p><strong>Motor Power:</strong> Tilting wet grinder motors range from 0.5 HP (for 5L models) to 3 HP (for 40L models). The motor must be powerful enough to turn the heavy granite stones even when loaded with ingredients. Under-powered motors strain during grinding, overheat, and fail prematurely. Always match motor power to capacity — don't buy a budget model with a weak motor to save money.</p>
    <p><strong>Tilting Mechanism:</strong> The tilting mechanism should be smooth and easy to operate even when the drum is full. Gear-type tilting mechanisms are more reliable than simple lever types. Check that the tilting locks securely in the upright position during grinding — you don't want the drum tilting mid-grind.</p>
    <p><strong>RPM:</strong> Wet grinders operate at much lower RPM than mixer grinders — typically 100–200 RPM. Lower RPM is intentional — slow grinding produces less heat and better batter quality. Some models offer variable speed, which is useful for different ingredients.</p>

    <h3>Top Tilting Wet Grinder Brands in India</h3>

    <p><strong>Lakshmi:</strong> The undisputed leader in commercial wet grinders. Based in Coimbatore, Lakshmi has been making wet grinders for decades and their tilting models are found in South Indian restaurants across the country and abroad. Excellent granite stones, robust construction, and a strong service network. If you buy one wet grinder brand, buy Lakshmi. Price premium over budget brands: 15–30%, but the reliability and batter quality justify it.</p>

    <p><strong>Premier:</strong> Another Coimbatore-based brand, Premier makes high-quality tilting wet grinders for commercial use. Known for good stone quality and smooth tilting mechanisms. Slightly more affordable than Lakshmi at comparable capacities. Excellent choice for budget-conscious buyers who don't want to compromise on quality.</p>

    <p><strong>Santha:</strong> A respected name in wet grinders, Santha makes commercial tilting models that are popular in Tamil Nadu and Kerala. Good quality, competitive pricing, and reliable after-sales service in South India. Less available in North India.</p>

    <p><strong>Elgi Ultra:</strong> The commercial arm of Ultra, Elgi makes large-capacity wet grinders for industrial and hotel use. Premium pricing, but excellent build quality and powerful motors. Good option for hotels and large restaurants.</p>

    <p><strong>Butterfly:</strong> Butterfly's wet grinder range is more popular in the domestic segment, but they offer some commercial models that work well for smaller restaurants. Good value for 5–10 litre capacities.</p>

    <h3>Tilting Wet Grinder vs Conventional Wet Grinder</h3>
    <p>For commercial use, always choose a tilting model over a conventional (non-tilting) wet grinder. Conventional wet grinders require you to scoop out the batter manually using a ladle, which is slow, messy, and inefficient when you're working with 10–40 litres of batter. The tilting mechanism pays for itself in time savings and reduced labour within a few weeks. The price difference between tilting and non-tilting is typically ₹3,000–₹8,000 — negligible compared to the daily convenience.</p>

