    <h2>5. Commercial Dry Grinder: Prices, Specs & Buying Guide</h2>

    <p>A commercial dry grinder is purpose-built for grinding dry ingredients into powders and fine flours. If your kitchen grinds its own spice blends (garam masala, sambar powder, rasam powder), makes its own flours (besan, rice flour, ragi flour), or processes dried ingredients in bulk, a dedicated commercial dry grinder is far more efficient than using the dry jar of a mixer grinder.</p>

    <h3>Types of Commercial Dry Grinders</h3>
    <p><strong>Plate-Type Dry Grinder:</strong> Uses two grinding plates (one stationary, one rotating) to crush and grind dry ingredients. Produces medium to fine powders. Good for spices, dried chillies, and coarse flours. Simple, durable, and affordable. Price: ₹10,000–₹25,000.</p>
    <p><strong>Hammer Mill Dry Grinder:</strong> Uses high-speed rotating hammers to pulverize ingredients against a screen. Produces fine to very fine powders. Better for finer flours and powdered spices. More expensive but faster and finer than plate grinders. Price: ₹18,000–₹45,000.</p>
    <p><strong>Stone Grinder (Chakki):</strong> Traditional stone mill using two grinding stones. Excellent for wheat flour (atta), gram flour (besan), and other grain flours where the traditional stone-ground taste is desired. Slower than plate or hammer mills but produces superior flour quality with nutrients intact. Price: ₹15,000–₹40,000.</p>

