    <h2>9. Maintenance, Spare Parts & Warranty</h2>

    <p>A commercial mixer grinder is a daily-use machine that takes significant abuse. Proper maintenance extends its life dramatically, while neglected machines fail prematurely and expensively. Here's a practical maintenance guide.</p>

    <h3>Daily Maintenance (5 Minutes)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Clean all jars immediately after use.</strong> Don't let masala residue dry inside jars — it hardens and corrodes blades over time. Rinse with warm water and a mild detergent, then dry.</li>
      <li><strong>Wipe the motor base.</strong> Keep the motor housing clean and dry. Moisture or food splatter on the motor base can cause short circuits.</li>
      <li><strong>Check jar gaskets/seals.</strong> Rubber seals wear out and cause leaks. Replace cracked or worn gaskets immediately — a leaking jar means liquid entering the blade assembly and eventually reaching the motor coupling.</li>
      <li><strong>For wet grinders:</strong> Rinse the drum and stones after each use. Remove any batter residue from between the stones and the drum wall.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Weekly Maintenance (15 Minutes)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Inspect blades.</strong> Check for chips, cracks, or excessive wear. Dull blades make the motor work harder and produce coarser results. Sharpen or replace blades as needed.</li>
      <li><strong>Check the motor coupling.</strong> The coupling between the motor and the jar assembly wears over time. Worn couplings cause slippage, noise, and reduced grinding efficiency.</li>
      <li><strong>Tighten any loose screws or fittings.</strong> Vibration from daily use loosens screws over time.</li>
      <li><strong>For wet grinders:</strong> Check that grinding stones are seated properly and haven't shifted. Inspect the drum for cracks or dents.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Monthly Maintenance (30 Minutes)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Lubricate bearings</strong> (if accessible) with food-grade lubricant.</li>
      <li><strong>Check electrical connections.</strong> Look for frayed wires, loose connections, or burn marks on plugs.</li>
      <li><strong>Test overload protection.</strong> Deliberately overload the machine briefly to confirm the overload protector trips correctly.</li>
      <li><strong>Deep clean the motor base.</strong> Open any accessible panels and remove accumulated dust and grease from the motor area (with the machine unplugged).</li>
    </ul>

